00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:14.570
But he did not
suffer fools gladly.

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:18.560
And here are a few
examples of definitions

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:20.440
from the original
"Devil's Dictionary."

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:23.170
This is probably his
best known definition.

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:25.580
Those of you who are
married-- [INAUDIBLE],

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:28.040
perhaps you can
sympathize with this.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:33.590
Love, noun-- a temporary
insanity curable by marriage.

00:04:33.590 --> 00:04:36.340
Another favorite of mine--
once you are in love,

00:04:36.340 --> 00:04:37.720
you should remember this.

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:41.020
Jealous, adjective--
unduly concerned

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:43.420
about the preservation
of that which

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:47.920
can be lost only if it
is not worth keeping.

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:51.880
Here's one of his few financial
definitions that's quite good.

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:54.710
Finance, noun--
the art or science

00:04:54.710 --> 00:04:57.530
of managing revenues and
resources for the best

00:04:57.530 --> 00:05:00.140
advantage of the manager.

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:03.540
And I've included this one.

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:09.240
It gives you a sense of how dark
Bierce's view of the world was.

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:12.330
I don't really
endorse his pessimism.

00:05:12.330 --> 00:05:13.940
You can draw your
own conclusions

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:15.600
about his personality.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:19.220
But I put it up
because those of you

00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:24.580
who buy "The Devil's Financial
Dictionary" will encounter

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:29.870
some definitions that I've
written that also feature

00:05:29.870 --> 00:05:31.830
these little-- I
call them flights

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:39.710
of fancy, in which an
imaginary character helps

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:41.410
us understand a definition.

00:05:41.410 --> 00:05:48.360
And in this case, Bierce is
giving two lines of poetry

00:05:48.360 --> 00:05:52.940
from a non-existent
medieval English poet

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:55.860
named [? Bori ?] the Bald.

00:05:55.860 --> 00:06:02.570
But in any case, so why did
I want to write this book?

00:06:02.570 --> 00:06:06.820
Well, some of you might be
familiar with the 19th century

00:06:06.820 --> 00:06:12.560
British essayist and historian
Thomas Carlyle, who is today

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:17.120
perhaps best known for
saying that economics

00:06:17.120 --> 00:06:23.290
is the dismal science,
which is a little quip

00:06:23.290 --> 00:06:28.070
that he made in an article he
wrote, I believe, in the 1840s.

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:32.230
And what I would argue after
almost 30 years of writing

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:35.750
about investing is
that if economics

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:42.280
is the dismal science, then
investing is the abysmal art.

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:49.690
It is rendered boring
and overly complicated.

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:53.940
A few words I've heard over the
years about various investing

00:06:53.940 --> 00:06:55.760
books are some of these.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:07:00.290
I'm sure anyone in this room
who's read a book on investing

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:04.200
might have adjectives of your
own you would tend to apply.

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:07.260
But it's never really
been clear to me

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:12.824
why there's no sense
of fun involved

00:07:12.824 --> 00:07:16.190
when we talk about
investing, and also

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:21.540
why so few people point
out the ridiculousness

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:27.030
and the absurdity that often
is involved when people manage

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:28.820
other people's money.

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:33.900
So that's some of the spirit I
wanted to get at in the book.

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:37.910
And the other thing
is it occurred to me

00:07:37.910 --> 00:07:43.730
as I was thinking
about recapturing some

00:07:43.730 --> 00:07:47.900
of the spirit of Ambrose
Bierce that maybe

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:53.070
if you can make people laugh,
you can help them learn.

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:55.450
And I think one of
the real pitfalls

00:07:55.450 --> 00:07:57.850
of traditional
financial advice is

00:07:57.850 --> 00:08:03.650
it's so somber and
deadly serious, and sort

00:08:03.650 --> 00:08:08.080
of self-referential, and
often self-righteous.

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:11.350
And one of the things I've
learned over the years

00:08:11.350 --> 00:08:13.620
is that yes, it's true.

00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:18.390
In the very long run,
financial markets and returns

00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:21.680
on investments-- they're
driven by economics,

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:26.230
the fundamental forces
of supply demand.

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:29.450
But in the short-term,
the medium-term,

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:34.039
even the fairly long-term for
many years on end-- 3 to 5,

00:08:34.039 --> 00:08:38.090
sometimes 10 years-- markets
are driven by psychology--

00:08:38.090 --> 00:08:43.510
often crowd psychology,
sometimes abnormal psychology.

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:51.750
And another wonderful thing that
a satirical dictionary format

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:58.250
enables a writer to do
is to look at etymology,

00:08:58.250 --> 00:09:00.630
the derivations of words.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:03.870
Because often one of
the things we pick up

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:07.490
when we learn where
words come from

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:13.840
is the hidden meanings that lurk
within the heart of terminology

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:18.190
we use every day without
really being very aware of it.

00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:24.280
One simple classic
example is-- and I'll

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:29.170
ask, does anybody in the room
know what do the words happy,

00:09:29.170 --> 00:09:35.270
happen, and perhaps
all have in common?

00:09:35.270 --> 00:09:37.090
Does anyone know
what the root word

00:09:37.090 --> 00:09:41.660
"hap" means in early English?

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:42.640
AUDIENCE: Chance.

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:44.650
JASON ZWEIG: Exactly.

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:46.050
Means luck.

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:49.690
So remember the next
time you're happy, which

00:09:49.690 --> 00:09:51.770
I hope will be in
a couple minutes

00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:55.710
from now, remember that you're
happy because you're lucky,

00:09:55.710 --> 00:10:00.170
and to some extent, to
be lucky is to be happy.

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:03.410
So I wanted to have some
fun with ideas like that.

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:10.130
But it's also I wanted to
bring in financial history

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:14.990
because one of the critical
things investors need to do

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:17.910
is learn from mistakes.

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:21.300
Now, we can learn
from our own mistakes,

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:24.150
but it's a lot cheaper to learn
from other people's mistakes,

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:25.590
right?

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:31.610
And a really simple, useful
definition of history

00:10:31.610 --> 00:10:35.800
is it's the record of
other people's mistakes,

00:10:35.800 --> 00:10:39.070
and also their regrets.

00:10:39.070 --> 00:10:41.770
So we can learn from that.

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:44.460
And then the final
thing that I think

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:49.100
satire is useful for is to
fight confirmation bias.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:53.120
To prevent us from
digging ourselves

00:10:53.120 --> 00:10:57.370
into an ever deeper hole
of our own decisions,

00:10:57.370 --> 00:11:00.600
and just constantly
drilling down

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:04.090
to prove that what we've
already done is right,

00:11:04.090 --> 00:11:08.730
and just to sink into this
sinkhole of our own sunk costs

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:10.530
until we can't get out.

00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:15.770
And if you can bring
a little sense of play

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:19.350
and make a little bit of
fun of people's ideas,

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:22.440
maybe you can jolt them
out of that complacency.

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:24.270
That at least was my hope.

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:29.550
So I'm just putting up one
illustration from the book

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:31.630
just to give you a
sense of the feel

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:34.500
that the publisher and
I wanted to get across.

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:39.680
Some you may recognize this is
a 16th century Dutch engraving

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:43.630
taken from a painting by the
great Dutch master Pieter

00:11:43.630 --> 00:11:45.390
Brueghel the Elder.

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:48.300
And this was
engraved around 1558.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:52.720
And the queenly character
sitting in the middle

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:56.410
is Avarizia, or greed.

00:11:56.410 --> 00:11:58.650
And you can see
all of these people

00:11:58.650 --> 00:12:02.870
and creatures are
worshipping her, serving her

00:12:02.870 --> 00:12:06.340
in one form or another,
filling her chest with gold.

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:08.340
Her lap is full of gold.

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:10.510
There's a frog in
the foreground,

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:12.320
or it might be a toad.

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:17.080
Frogs and toads were symbols
of greed in medieval Europe.

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:19.810
And there are all kinds
of other things going on.

00:12:19.810 --> 00:12:21.670
And at the risk of
bothering people

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:24.010
who are eating their
lunch, I'll point out

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:29.070
that on the far
right, a stork is

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:37.640
feeding from the bottom of that
figure immediately to the left.

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:41.490
And so I wanted
to give you a few

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:43.050
of the definitions
in the book just

00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:46.750
to give you a feel for
what I'm trying to do.

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:54.170
And those of you who are in
the market for financial advice

00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:57.340
should probably keep
these first two in mind.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:02.510
So big producer, noun-- a
stock broker or insurance agent

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:05.100
who produces big commissions.

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:07.650
The term is erroneous, however.

00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:11.080
The broker or agent doesn't
produce the commissions.

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:13.650
It is his clients
who produce them.

00:13:13.650 --> 00:13:16.760
He just collects them.

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:21.970
So then financial
advisor-- often

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:25.670
someone who cares deeply
about being prudent, diligent,

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:28.480
competent, and
honest, in which case

00:13:28.480 --> 00:13:31.610
his or her services
will be priceless.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:34.360
Sometimes, someone
who cares only

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:37.300
about being a big
producer, in which case

00:13:37.300 --> 00:13:38.803
you are in for big trouble.

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:44.860
This is one of my
favorite definitions.

00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:46.810
It's very short.

00:13:46.810 --> 00:13:51.350
Potential conflict of interest,
noun-- an actual conflict

00:13:51.350 --> 00:13:51.850
of interest.

00:13:54.920 --> 00:13:58.740
Every prospectus you
read, every document

00:13:58.740 --> 00:14:01.430
your financial advisor
might hand you,

00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:06.780
will mention this term,
potential conflict of interest.

00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:08.820
And you should remember
that the real meaning

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:11.580
is actual conflict of interest.

00:14:15.100 --> 00:14:22.390
Forecasting, noun-- the attempt
to predict the unknowable

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:26.160
by measuring the irrelevant.

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:28.730
A task that in
one way or another

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:31.850
employs most people
on Wall Street.

00:14:31.850 --> 00:14:35.090
Because the human mind
hates admitting the truth

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:38.510
that the world is largely
random and unpredictable,

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:40.910
forecasters will
always be in demand

00:14:40.910 --> 00:14:43.430
regardless of their futility.

00:14:43.430 --> 00:14:46.440
Wall Street follows what
marketing Professor J. Scott

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:49.660
Armstrong has called
the seer-sucker theory.

00:14:49.660 --> 00:14:52.960
For every seer,
there is a sucker.

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:55.960
In the real world, as
with weather forecasts

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:58.740
or predictions about who
will win a sporting event,

00:14:58.740 --> 00:15:00.880
those making the
projections typically

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:04.210
estimate the likelihood
that they are correct.

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.360
Wall Street forecasts,
on the other hand,

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:10.180
almost never have
probabilities attached.

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:14.630
As decision scientist Baruch
Fischhoff wrote in 1994,

00:15:14.630 --> 00:15:18.200
when both forecaster
and client exaggerate

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:21.110
the quality of
forecasts, the client

00:15:21.110 --> 00:15:23.175
will often win the
race to the poorhouse.

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:29.250
And long-term is another
favorite of mine,

00:15:29.250 --> 00:15:31.660
and I think it's one that's
very useful for people

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:33.310
to bear in mind.

00:15:33.310 --> 00:15:37.230
Long-term, adjective--
on Wall Street, a phrase

00:15:37.230 --> 00:15:41.610
used to describe a period that
begins approximately 30 seconds

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:45.635
from now and ends at most
a few weeks from now.

