00:56:13.300 --> 00:56:16.250
And if you would have,
why would you have?

00:56:16.250 --> 00:56:18.560
JASON ZWEIG: Yeah.

00:56:18.560 --> 00:56:21.770
I think in the 70s,
very few people

00:56:21.770 --> 00:56:24.110
would have named Warren Buffett.

00:56:24.110 --> 00:56:26.650
And there's a really
interesting, useful lesson

00:56:26.650 --> 00:56:28.602
in that.

00:56:28.602 --> 00:56:32.470
In many cases, just
given the standard

00:56:32.470 --> 00:56:34.440
margins of
out-performance we tend

00:56:34.440 --> 00:56:38.220
to observe in the
stock market where

00:56:38.220 --> 00:56:43.690
someone who out-performs a
benchmark like the S&amp;P 500

00:56:43.690 --> 00:56:48.900
by 1 percentage point
a year compounded

00:56:48.900 --> 00:56:51.400
is regarded as an
extraordinary achievement.

00:56:51.400 --> 00:56:55.710
So over a period when
stocks are up 7% or 8%,

00:56:55.710 --> 00:56:59.570
someone who earns 8% or
9% gets an enormous amount

00:56:59.570 --> 00:57:01.020
of favorable attention.

00:57:01.020 --> 00:57:03.480
It's a pretty narrow margin.

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:08.680
And then given the standard
deviation that is usually

00:57:08.680 --> 00:57:10.890
embedded in a track
record like that,

00:57:10.890 --> 00:57:16.060
often you need 50 to 80
years to have 95% confidence

00:57:16.060 --> 00:57:19.360
that the person is
skillful and not lucky.

00:57:19.360 --> 00:57:22.560
And at that point,
you've pretty much

00:57:22.560 --> 00:57:27.980
dealt with a human lifespan--
your own and the money manager.

00:57:27.980 --> 00:57:31.710
So there's kind of a
paradox that by the time

00:57:31.710 --> 00:57:33.680
you can be confident
that the person is

00:57:33.680 --> 00:57:36.880
really good at what
he or she is doing,

00:57:36.880 --> 00:57:40.030
you're both about to die.

00:57:40.030 --> 00:57:43.220
So I don't think most
people would have

00:57:43.220 --> 00:57:46.010
identified Buffett in the 70s.

00:57:46.010 --> 00:57:49.290
Quite a few did in the 1980s.

00:57:49.290 --> 00:57:52.160
Carol Loomis, the great
financial journalist

00:57:52.160 --> 00:57:55.620
at "Fortune" identified
him almost immediately

00:57:55.620 --> 00:57:58.740
when she met him in the 60s.

00:57:58.740 --> 00:58:00.720
Carol is a good friend of mine.

00:58:00.720 --> 00:58:04.310
And some other
people did, as well.

00:58:04.310 --> 00:58:08.810
But most people who've
invested in Berkshire Hathaway

00:58:08.810 --> 00:58:11.560
arrived later.

00:58:11.560 --> 00:58:13.850
The ones who made the
most money from Berkshire

00:58:13.850 --> 00:58:17.570
are the ones who
