01:02:12.410 --> 01:02:15.464
AUDIENCE: My question
is on the definition

01:02:15.464 --> 01:02:18.880
of potential
conflict of interest.

01:02:18.880 --> 01:02:21.430
In managing other
people's money,

01:02:21.430 --> 01:02:25.660
do you see any
model that does not

01:02:25.660 --> 01:02:29.800
have the potential of
conflict of interest?

01:02:29.800 --> 01:02:33.250
And then follow-up on it is
what do you think about the VC

01:02:33.250 --> 01:02:37.980
model, where they charge
management a fee, and and 20%

01:02:37.980 --> 01:02:39.010
on the profit, I think?

01:02:39.010 --> 01:02:40.310
JASON ZWEIG: Right.

01:02:40.310 --> 01:02:48.930
Well, there are many groups in
the asset management business

01:02:48.930 --> 01:02:54.240
who will tell you that they
have no conflict of interest.

01:02:54.240 --> 01:02:58.340
In fact, I had a long email
dialogue about a year ago

01:02:58.340 --> 01:03:02.830
with a financial
adviser who said to me,

01:03:02.830 --> 01:03:08.430
my financial planning
practice is conflict-free.

01:03:08.430 --> 01:03:11.490
I have no conflicts
of interest at all.

01:03:11.490 --> 01:03:14.100
Just ask my clients.

01:03:14.100 --> 01:03:18.760
And I tried to point out to him
that, in fact, no matter how

01:03:18.760 --> 01:03:23.560
he charges, he can't help but
have conflicts of interest.

01:03:23.560 --> 01:03:25.350
In fact, if he
didn't charge at all,

01:03:25.350 --> 01:03:27.810
he would still have a conflict.

01:03:27.810 --> 01:03:31.050
There's an irreducible
conflict in the fact

01:03:31.050 --> 01:03:33.320
that someone who is
managing your money

01:03:33.320 --> 01:03:37.880
is managing your money,
not his or her own.

01:03:37.880 --> 01:03:42.410
And I don't think there's
any way to eliminate that.

01:03:42.410 --> 01:03:48.390
The key is for the asset
manager and the client

01:03:48.390 --> 01:03:51.310
to be on the same
page and to understand

01:03:51.310 --> 01:03:54.980
where the conflicts are
and what the conflicts are.

01:03:54.980 --> 01:03:58.050
So someone who is charging,
for example, 2 and 20

01:03:58.050 --> 01:04:02.370
as a hedge fund might,
or some VC funds might,

01:04:02.370 --> 01:04:08.790
has a clear incentive to raise
money, hang onto the money,

01:04:08.790 --> 01:04:12.930
often take very
substantial risks.

01:04:12.930 --> 01:04:15.510
And one of the things
you want to look for--

01:04:15.510 --> 01:04:18.200
and again, this is just
a bit of general advice--

01:04:18.200 --> 01:04:21.860
is as engineers, you're
very familiar with this sort

01:04:21.860 --> 01:04:22.770
of approach.

01:04:22.770 --> 01:04:25.050
You want to look at
the dispersion, right?

01:04:25.050 --> 01:04:29.240
You want to say, well, who
out there is doing this

01:04:29.240 --> 01:04:31.970
more cheaply, and
what does it look

01:04:31.970 --> 01:04:34.870
like over at this end
of the distribution?

01:04:34.870 --> 01:04:37.510
And then who's doing it
much more expensively,

01:04:37.510 --> 01:04:39.180
and what does that look like?

01:04:39.180 --> 01:04:44.530
And then where in that continuum
does this person or fund fall?

01:04:44.530 --> 01:04:46.580
And am I comfortable with that?

01:04:46.580 --> 01:04:49.920
Is there a better,
cheaper way to do it?

01:04:49.920 --> 01:04:55.430
Or do the results seem to
be improved by higher fees?

01:04:55.430 --> 01:05:00.540
I mean, I guess it's
theoretically possible.

01:05:00.540 --> 01:05:02.920
But certainly what
you want to do

01:05:02.920 --> 01:05:06.590
is you want to look at
the alternative ways

01:05:06.590 --> 01:05:10.900
that you could be charged, and
ask yourself whether you're

01:05:10.900 --> 01:05:14.720
more comfortable with one of
those other models of paying

01:05:14.720 --> 01:05:16.800
fees rather than this one.

01:05:16.800 --> 01:05:23.020
You don't have to pay 2 and
20 if you don't want to.

01:05:23.020 --> 01:05:25.230
You might get stuck
doing it if you

01:05:25.230 --> 01:05:28.520
like the people or
the process, but I

01:05:28.520 --> 01:05:32.150
don't think you should accept
any fee structure as a given

01:05:32.150 --> 01:05:34.970
or set in stone.

01:05:34.970 --> 01:05:40.230
Increasingly there's
a diversity of ways

01:05:40.230 --> 01:05:43.120
people will charge
to manage your money,

01:05:43.120 --> 01:05:47.710
and I think, also, individual
investors tend to underestimate

01:05:47.710 --> 01:05:50.910
their own negotiating power.

01:05:50.910 --> 01:05:55.920
You should always get the form
80V, which is the standard SEC

01:05:55.920 --> 01:05:58.970
disclosure that any
registered investment

01:05:58.970 --> 01:06:01.400
adviser has to provide.

01:06:01.400 --> 01:06:04.510
And often, when
you read the 80V,

01:06:04.510 --> 01:06:07.350
you will see something
very interesting

01:06:07.350 --> 01:06:10.730
that the person you met
with never mentioned.

01:06:10.730 --> 01:06:12.600
Our fees are negotiable.

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:20.460
Very few asset managers
will volunteer that fact,

01:06:20.460 --> 01:06:24.810
but by law, if
they may negotiate,

01:06:24.810 --> 01:06:30.440
they must say they negotiate
in the disclosure form.

01:06:30.440 --> 01:06:33.880
They don't have to
tell you directly,

01:06:33.880 --> 01:06:36.340
but they do have to tell
you in the disclosure form.

01:06:36.340 --> 01:06:39.520
And if you see it there,
you should bring it with you

01:06:39.520 --> 01:06:41.170
when you meet with the person.

01:06:41.170 --> 01:06:46.410
So I would just encourage you to
be as aggressive on that front

01:06:46.410 --> 01:06:49.380
as you're comfortable
being because fees

01:06:49.380 --> 01:06:53.230
are the primary determinant
of the difference

01:06:53.230 --> 01:06:57.230
between good performance
and great performance.

01:06:57.230 --> 01:07:01.100
And it's one thing that
you can control probably

01:07:01.100 --> 01:07:03.890
much more so than you've
been led to believe.

01:07:03.890 --> 01:07:06.600
So I would just encourage that.

